---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="About the Community Mobilization Skills Hub.">

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">About this project</span>
      <h1>Where this came from.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        The Community Mobilization Skills Hub is a learning resource built alongside the Field Manual — making the 10 core skills accessible to practitioners at every stage of the journey.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <div class="prose">

        <h2>What this hub is</h2>
        <p>
          This is a companion to the Community Mobilization Field Manual — a digital resource that brings the 10 core skills to life with definitions, examples, guiding questions, and proficiency frameworks that practitioners can use in real time.
        </p>
        <p>
          It is designed for Executive Directors, program staff, and community partners who are doing the work of building resilient, self-determined communities. It is not a certification program. It is not a checklist. It is a learning environment.
        </p>

        <h2>What community mobilization is</h2>
        <p>
          Community mobilization is an approach — not a program. It is the process of identifying and bringing together community stakeholders to raise awareness of and demand for resources, to assist in delivery of services, and to strengthen community participation for sustainability and self-reliance.
        </p>
        <p>
          The skills in this hub are the tools for that work. They are not job titles or departments. They are practices — things that can be learned, developed, and deepened over time.
        </p>

        <h2>How to use this resource</h2>
        <p>
          This hub is modular. You do not move through it front to back. You go where the work takes you. Preparing for a community meeting? Start with Purposeful Meetings. Trying to understand who holds power in a room? Start with Who Speaks Matters. Wanting to understand yourself before understanding your community? Start with Self-Discovery.
        </p>
        <p>
          Each skill page includes a definition, examples from Red Cross work and everyday life, guiding questions for reflection, and a proficiency framework that helps you understand where you are and what growth looks like.
        </p>

        <h2>Core beliefs</h2>
        <blockquote>
          Communities are co-creators — not recipients. They have assets, knowledge, and leadership that must be at the center.
        </blockquote>
        <ul>
          <li>Trust is not a step in the process — it is the process.</li>
          <li>Power dynamics are always present. Ignoring them does not make them go away.</li>
          <li>Listening comes before planning. Always.</li>
          <li>Proficiency is a journey, not a destination. We are all somewhere on the path.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>A note on language</h2>
        <p>
          We use the word <strong>proficiency</strong> rather than mastery — because mastery implies an endpoint, and this work never ends. The four proficiency levels (Understand It, Can Do It, Do It Consistently, Coach/Mentor Others) are not evaluations. They are invitations to honest self-reflection.
        </p>

      </div>

      <div style="margin-top: 3rem; padding: 2rem; background: var(--surf-2); border-radius: var(--r-lg); border-left: 4px solid var(--people);">
        <h3 style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Ready to start?</h3>
        <p style="color: var(--ink-2); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">Begin with the overview to understand the full picture, or go directly to the skills.</p>
        <div style="display: flex; gap: 0.75rem; flex-wrap: wrap;">
          <a href="/overview" class="btn btn-primary">Read the overview</a>
          <a href="/skills" class="btn btn-outline">Browse the skills</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
